definition.value: An abnormal concentration of urobilinogen in the urine.
An abnormally reduced concentration of urobilinogen in the urine.
An abnormal concentration of vitamin B6 in the blood circulation.
An abnormally increased concentration of vitamin B6 in the blood circulation.

label.value: Abnormal pituitary glycoprotein hormone alpha subunit level

definition.value: Any deviation from the normal concentration of circulating alpha polypeptide of glycoprotein hormones (NCBI Gene 1081).

label.value: Decreased pituitary glycoprotein hormone alpha subunit level

definition.value: An reduced concentration of circulating alpha polypeptide of glycoprotein hormones (NCBI Gene 1081).
Abnormal concentration of feces as assessed by the total number of solute particles per kilogram.
Abnormally high concentration of feces as assessed by the total number of solute particles per kilogram.
Abnormally low concentration of feces as assessed by the total number of solute particles per kilogram.

Any deviation from the normal pH of feces. The pH reflects the acidity or alkalinity of a solution on a logarithmic scale on which 7 is neutral, whereby lower values are more acid and higher values more alkaline.
Abnormally high fecal pH, i.e., abnormal alkalinity of feces.
Abnormally low fecal pH, i.e., abnormal acidity of feces.
Fasciculations affecting the tongue muscle and the musculature of the chin.
Onychotillomania is characterized by the compulsive or irresistible urge in patients to pick at, pull off, or harmfully bite or chew their nails.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to a tendon.
The position of the umbilicus (belly button) is abnormally high (superior).
Reduced strength of the masseter muscle, whose primary function is to elevate the mandible and thereby raise the mandible towards the maxilla, closing the jaw.
The position of the umbilicus (belly button) is abnormally low (inferior).
An increased amount of 4-hydroxybutyric acid in the urine.
